  <p>Most Melbourne homeowners don't think about their chimney until something goes wrong — smoke filling the room, a fire that won't stay lit, or a smell that lingers long after the last log burns out. By that point, the buildup is usually significant. Here's how to tell if your chimney needs cleaning before it becomes a problem.</p>

  <h2>1. Smoke Is Coming Back Into the Room</h2>

  <p>This is the most obvious sign and the one that sends people straight to the phone. If you light a fire and smoke drifts back into the living room instead of going up the flue, something is blocking or restricting the airflow. The most common cause is creosote and soot buildup narrowing the flue, but bird nests and debris blockages can do the same thing.</p>

  <p>A chimney that used to draw well and now doesn't is almost always a cleaning issue. A chimney that has never drawn well may have a structural or design problem — but a professional clean is still the first step to rule that out.</p>

  <h2>2. There's a Persistent Smoky Smell When the Fire Isn't On</h2>

  <p>Creosote has a strong, acrid smell — somewhere between burnt wood and tar. If you can smell it in the room even when no fire has been lit recently, the flue walls are coated enough that the odour is seeping through. This is particularly noticeable in warm weather or when humidity is high, as moisture activates the smell.</p>

  <p>A faint campfire scent after using the fireplace is normal. A smell that lingers for days, or that you can detect in the room without having lit a fire at all, is not.</p>

  <h2>3. The Fire Burns Sluggishly or Is Hard to Keep Alight</h2>

  <p>A well-drawing chimney creates a strong upward airflow that feeds oxygen to the fire. When the flue is restricted with soot or creosote, that airflow weakens. You'll notice fires that take longer to get going, struggle to stay lit without constant attention, or burn much lower and cooler than they used to.</p>

  <p>If you've ruled out wet or poor-quality wood, a blocked flue is the next most likely cause. It's one of the most common reasons Melbourne homeowners call us in autumn — the heater worked fine last season, sat unused all summer, and now it won't perform.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>Quick test: hold a lit match or lighter near the firebox opening before lighting a fire. The flame should be drawn inward toward the flue. If it flickers outward or doesn't move, airflow is restricted.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>4. You Can See Heavy Black Soot Around the Firebox</h2>

  <p>Some soot around the firebox and throat is normal. Heavy, greasy or oily black deposits — especially if they've spread outside the firebox onto the surround — indicate significant creosote buildup. Creosote in its early stages is a dry grey or black powder. More advanced buildup is tar-like, sticky, and in severe cases hardens into a glassy coating that's difficult to remove.</p>

  <p>If you can see it at the firebox level, there's considerably more further up the flue where you can't see it.</p>

  <h2>5. You Can Hear Animals or See Debris Falling Into the Firebox</h2>

  <p>Melbourne's spring and summer months are nesting season. Starlings, sparrows and other birds frequently nest in unused chimneys, and the nests — built from twigs, grass and debris — can completely block the flue. If you hear scratching or chirping from the chimney, or notice twigs and leaf litter dropping into the firebox, you have a blockage that needs clearing before you light any fires.</p>

  <p>Lighting a fire with a bird nest in the flue is a serious fire hazard. The nest material ignites easily and can cause a chimney fire.</p>

  <h2>6. It's Been More Than 12 Months Since the Last Clean</h2>

  <p>Even if you have no obvious symptoms, a chimney that's been used regularly through a Melbourne winter needs an annual clean. Creosote builds up gradually — you won't notice it happening until the restriction becomes significant. By the time the symptoms above appear, there's usually a considerable amount of buildup already present.</p>

  <p>The standard professional recommendation is once per year for regular use. If you burn every night through winter, or if you've been burning unseasoned wood or softwoods like pine, you may need cleaning more frequently.</p>

  <h2>7. You've Just Moved Into the Property</h2>

  <p>Unknown service history is reason enough. A chimney that looks clean from the firebox can have years of creosote coating the upper flue where it's not visible. If you've bought or rented a property with a fireplace or wood heater and you don't know when it was last cleaned, get it inspected and cleaned before you use it — regardless of how it looks or performs on the first couple of fires.</p>

